body:
V3Inline just happens to do the right thing for `ref` ports, but they don't work if the module with the `ref` port is not inlined. I can't see documentation about support for `ref` ports being limited, and more importantly some times we can't inline modules at all, so this might be hit without warning.

Test:

```systemverilog
`define stop $stop
`define check(got ,exp) do if ((got) !== (exp)) begin $write("%%Error: %s:%0d: cyc=%0d got='%0d exp='%0d\n", `__FILE__,`__LINE__, cyc, (got), (exp)); `stop; end while(0)

module top;

  bit clk = 0;
  always #5 clk = ~clk;

  int cyc = 0;
  int x;

  sub s(clk, cyc, x);

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    cyc <= cyc + 1;
    if (cyc == 0) begin
      // Ignore
    end else if (cyc == 1) begin
      // 'x' updated by 'sub'
    end else if (cyc == 2) begin
      `check(x, 100);
    end else if (cyc == 3) begin
      x <= 200;
    end else if (cyc == 4) begin
      `check(x, 200);
    end else begin
      $write("*-* All Finished *-*\n");
      $finish;
    end
   end

endmodule

module sub(
  input bit clk,
  input int cyc,
  ref int y
);

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (cyc == 0) begin
      // Ignore
    end else if (cyc == 1) begin
      y <= 100;
    end else if (cyc == 2) begin
      `check(y, 100);
    end else if (cyc == 3) begin
      // 'y' updated by 'top'
    end else if (cyc == 4) begin
      `check(y, 200); // <-------------- Fails this check 
    end
   end

endmodule
```

Command line:
```
verilator --binary refport.sv -fno-inline -Wno-BLKANDNBLK
```

Note with `-fno-inline` we also get a seemingly stray `-Wno-BLKANDNBLK`. It's probably from the ~~AstAssignAlias created by V3Inline, which is treated as a combinational assignment~~ pin assignment created later.

Execution fails:

```
%Error: refport.sv:56: cyc=4 got='100 exp='200
%Error: refport.sv:56: Verilog $stop
Aborting...
```

This is because without the inlining, the created ~~AstAssignAlias~~ pin assignment is executed as `x = y`, so the update from the submodule is visible to the top module, but not the other way around.

Tracked down while looking into #6280 

An alternative way to implement ref ports would be to treat them as a parameter, and specialize the module using the hierarchical reference it is bound to. Maybe?

